menu "nimble-ble-proxy"

config NBP_WIFI
    bool "Bring up WiFi STA + HTTP API (dashboard, OTA, aioesphomeapi)"
    default y
    help
        Master switch for every WiFi-dependent subsystem: the STA
        connect, mDNS announce, the OTA / dashboard httpd listener,
        and the aioesphomeapi TCP server on port 6053.

        Turn off to ship a BLE-only build. The radios stay BLE-only;
        the HA proxy and the web dashboard disappear with it (until
        a BLE-side transport is added). NimBLE scanner + clone
        continue to work unchanged.

config NBP_OTA
    bool "Expose HTTP OTA endpoint (/update) for remote firmware flash"
    depends on NBP_WIFI
    default y
    help
        Register the POST /update handler that streams a raw .bin into
        the inactive OTA slot and reboots. Turn off for a "lockdown"
        build where firmware can only be updated over serial — useful
        for production deployments on untrusted LANs since OTA over
        plain HTTP is a write primitive for anyone who can reach the
        device.

        Disabling drops the app_update component dependency (~12 KB
        flash) and removes /update from the httpd. The shared httpd
        listener stays up so the dashboard, /stats.json, /clone, etc.
        keep working.

        The partition table still reserves two OTA slots either way —
        re-flash via serial picks ota_0 by default. To roll back to
        a single-slot factory layout edit partitions.csv.

config NBP_LIVENESS_WDT
    bool "Self-recovery liveness watchdog (reboot on upstream-LAN loss)"
    depends on NBP_WIFI
    default y
    help
        Spawn a supervisor task that probes upstream LAN reachability
        (STA default gateway + a known-open host) every
        NBP_LIVENESS_INTERVAL_SECS. After NBP_LIVENESS_THRESHOLD
        consecutive cycles where ALL targets are unreachable, it calls
        esp_restart().

        Recovers a total network wedge (a WiFi/coex livelock under heavy
        forwarded throughput) where tasks stay alive — so the IDF
        Task-WDT never fires — but the IP path is dead, which otherwise
        needs a physical power-cycle. Runtime-tunable / disable via
        POST /liveness?enabled=0; GET /liveness reports state.

config NBP_LIVENESS_INTERVAL_SECS
    int "Liveness: seconds between probe cycles"
    depends on NBP_LIVENESS_WDT
    default 30
    range 5 3600

config NBP_LIVENESS_THRESHOLD
    int "Liveness: consecutive failed cycles before reboot"
    depends on NBP_LIVENESS_WDT
    default 6
    range 1 60
    help
        Default 6 × 30 s ≈ 3 min of sustained unreachability before a
        reboot — comfortably longer than a normal STA reconnect, so a
        brief AP blip self-heals without rebooting.

config NBP_AP_FALLBACK
    bool "SoftAP fallback + provisioning page when STA can't associate"
    depends on NBP_WIFI
    default n
    help
        If the WiFi STA can't get an IP within NBP_AP_FALLBACK_SECS
        (bad creds, AP down, no creds set at all), bring up a SoftAP
        named "<hostname>-setup" and serve a single page at
        http://192.168.4.1/ that exposes:
          POST /wifi?ssid=...&psk=...   write to NVS, then reboot
        Replaces the "edit wifi_creds.h + re-flash" workflow with a
        runtime provisioning step — high value for distributing
        prebuilt binaries.

        Credential lookup order at boot:
          1. NVS namespace "wifi", keys "ssid" / "psk" (set via /wifi)
          2. WIFI_SSID / WIFI_PASSWORD from include/wifi_creds.h, if
             that header exists (now optional with this gate on)
          3. neither set → go straight to AP fallback

        Costs ~15 KB flash and one extra netif + httpd code path that
        only links when this gate is on. While the AP is up no other
        subsystem starts (mDNS, api_server, clone) — the device
        deliberately stays in provisioning mode until the user
        submits creds and it reboots.

config NBP_AP_FALLBACK_SECS
    int "SoftAP fallback: STA association timeout (seconds)"
    depends on NBP_AP_FALLBACK
    default 30
    range 5 300
    help
        How long to wait for the STA to acquire an IP before giving
        up and switching the radio into SoftAP provisioning mode.
        Bumping this is harmless on a healthy network; lower it for
        faster recovery when the configured AP is known-bad.

config NBP_WS_PROXY
    bool "WebSocket bridge: aioesphomeapi over ws://<host>/api (browser clients)"
    depends on NBP_WIFI
    select HTTPD_WS_SUPPORT
    default n
    help
        Add a binary WebSocket route at GET /api on the shared dashboard
        httpd. Each WS message carries raw plaintext aioesphomeapi protocol
        bytes; the bridge relays them verbatim to/from the existing TCP
        api_server over an on-device loopback connection (127.0.0.1:6053).
        This lets a browser (e.g. a JS port of aioesphomeapi) drive the BLE
        proxy — Hello/DeviceInfo, advertisement subscriptions, GATT
        connect/read/write/notify — even though browsers can't open a raw
        TCP socket.

        The api_server protocol code is untouched: from its side the
        browser is just another HA client on a normal TCP connection, so
        the handshake, Bluetooth* handlers, send_async broadcast and
        dead-fd reaping all apply unchanged. Selects HTTPD_WS_SUPPORT.

        Cost per connected browser: one loopback socket here + one accepted
        socket and an 8 KiB connection task inside api_server + a ~4 KiB
        pump task. Concurrent bridges are capped (MAX_WS_SESSIONS=2) so a
        page can't exhaust the 16-socket LWIP budget shared with httpd,
        mDNS and clone. Disable for builds that only ever talk to HA over
        plain TCP.

config NBP_NAT_ROUTER
    bool "WiFi NAT router: SoftAP + NAPT out the STA uplink"
    depends on NBP_WIFI
    default n
    select LWIP_IP_FORWARD
    select LWIP_IPV4_NAPT
    select LWIP_IPV4_NAPT_PORTMAP
    help
        Turn the proxy into a small travel-router. The device already
        joins an upstream WiFi as a station (wifi_sta); with this gate
        on it ALSO brings up its own SoftAP in APSTA mode and NATs
        traffic from AP clients out through the STA uplink.

        Clients that associate to the SoftAP get a 192.168.x.x lease
        from the on-device DHCP server (with the upstream DNS handed
        down), and their traffic is source-NAT'd onto the STA's IP.
        Inbound port-forwarding rules ("ext TCP/UDP port -> internal
        client ip:port") are configurable at runtime from the dashboard
        and persisted in NVS.

        Selects the lwIP IP_FORWARD / NAPT / NAPT_PORTMAP options, so
        they only compile in when this gate is on — a normal BLE-proxy
        build pays nothing. The SoftAP shares the STA's radio channel
        (single-radio constraint), so the STA link is unaffected.

config NBP_NAT_AP_SSID
    string "NAT SoftAP SSID (default; runtime-overridable via /nat)"
    depends on NBP_NAT_ROUTER
    default "nimble-nat"
    help
        Compile-time default SSID for the NAT SoftAP. Overridable at
        runtime from the dashboard (POST /nat), persisted in NVS.

config NBP_NAT_AP_PASSWORD
    string "NAT SoftAP WPA2 password (8..63 chars; <8 = open AP)"
    depends on NBP_NAT_ROUTER
    default "nimble-proxy"
    help
        Default WPA2-PSK password. A value shorter than 8 characters
        makes the AP open (no encryption). Runtime-overridable via the
        dashboard, persisted in NVS.

config NBP_NAT_AP_IP
    string "NAT SoftAP gateway IP (/24)"
    depends on NBP_NAT_ROUTER
    default "192.168.4.1"
    help
        IPv4 address of the SoftAP interface; also the gateway + DHCP
        server address handed to clients. The subnet is always /24.

config NBP_NAT_AP_MAX_CONN
    int "NAT SoftAP max simultaneous clients"
    depends on NBP_NAT_ROUTER
    default 4
    range 1 10
    help
        Upper bound on associated stations. Each client consumes a
        DHCP lease + NAPT table headroom.

config NBP_NAT_PORTMAP_MAX
    int "NAT port-forwarding table size"
    depends on NBP_NAT_ROUTER
    default 16
    range 1 32
    help
        Number of inbound port-forwarding rules that can be stored.
        Capped at 32 by lwIP's IP_PORTMAP_MAX. Each slot costs a few
        bytes of BSS plus one NVS blob entry.

config NBP_NAT_THROUGHPUT
    bool "Report SoftAP throughput (dashboard repeater chart)"
    depends on NBP_NAT_ROUTER
    default y
    help
        Tally bytes forwarded between the SoftAP clients and the STA
        uplink, split by direction, and expose them as "ap_rx"/"ap_tx"
        in /stats.json so the dashboard can draw a live repeater
        throughput chart (KB/s up/down). The chart self-hides when the
        fields are absent, so turning this off cleanly removes it.

        Implemented as an observe-only lwIP forward hook
        (LWIP_HOOK_IP4_CANFORWARD in nat_router.cpp) that adds each
        forwarded datagram's length to an up/down counter and returns
        "no decision". Cost is a short critical section per forwarded
        packet plus two 64-bit counters; off, the hook compiles out
        entirely and lwIP's forward path is untouched.

config NBP_BLE
    bool "Enable BLE (NimBLE scanner/proxy + all BLE features)"
    default y
    select BT_ENABLED
    help
        Master switch for the entire BLE side of the proxy. ON (the
        default) pulls in the NimBLE controller + host (selects
        BT_ENABLED; the host choice is pinned to NimBLE in
        sdkconfig.defaults) and compiles the BLE backend: the
        observer/central scanner that forwards advertisements to Home
        Assistant, the per-peer GATT client pool, and the BluetoothProxy
        half of the aioesphomeapi protocol. Every optional BLE feature
        nested below (ble_httpd dashboard, clone, SMP pairing, radio
        auto-off, the live device table) lives under this gate.

        Turn OFF to build a BLE-free firmware: no scanner, no
        BluetoothProxy API, and the NimBLE stack itself is left out of
        the image entirely (BT_ENABLED is no longer selected), reclaiming
        its flash + RAM. Only the WiFi-side subsystems remain — use this
        for a pure NAT-router / dashboard build.

        NOTE: turning this off together with NBP_WIFI leaves the device
        with no remote transport at all (no HTTP, no api_server, no BLE
        dashboard) — it would be reachable only over serial. Keep at
        least one of NBP_WIFI / NBP_BLE on.

if NBP_BLE

config NBP_BLE_HTTPD
    bool "BLE-side HTTP transport (GATT request/response service)"
    default n
    select BT_NIMBLE_ROLE_PERIPHERAL  if BT_NIMBLE_ENABLED
    select BT_NIMBLE_ROLE_BROADCASTER if BT_NIMBLE_ENABLED
    help
        Expose a NimBLE peripheral GATT service that carries simple
        request/response messages (HTTP-like). Lets a Web Bluetooth
        page act as the dashboard frontend when NBP_WIFI is off.

        Service / characteristic UUIDs:
          service   6e627062-7072-7879-0001-000000000000
          REQUEST   ...0001  (write — client → device, fragmented)
          RESPONSE  ...0002  (notify — device → client, fragmented)
          INFO      ...0003  (read — MTU + protocol version)

        Framing per fragment: [u8 flags][u8 reqId][payload].
        flags bit0 = FIN (last fragment), bit1 = ERR.

        Note: this stub advertises its own service UUID. If NBP_CLONE
        is also enabled, NimBLE has a single advertising context — only
        one of them gets advertised at a time. A real coordination
        layer can be added later.

config NBP_BLE_AUTO_OFF
    bool "Auto-quiesce the BLE radio when nothing needs it"
    default n
    help
        When on, a small supervisor task watches who actually needs the
        radio and quiesces it when idle, in two independent tiers:

          - Central role (the continuous, duty-cycled scan — the dominant
            power draw): paused whenever NO ESPHome API client is
            connected AND no GATT links are open AND BLE clone is
            inactive. Resumed instantly when any of those reappears.

          - Peripheral role (advertising the ble_httpd dashboard / clone
            mirror): suspended only when WiFi (STA) is connected AND no
            central is connected to us AND clone is inactive. Kept ON
            whenever WiFi is down, because then BLE is the only path to
            the dashboard (see NBP_BLE_HTTPD).

        When both tiers are idle and no links exist, the controller has
        no scan/adv/connection activity and drops to its lowest idle
        power without a full deinit — so the cloned/ble_httpd GATT DB
        (one-shot in NimBLE) survives and the radio comes straight back.

        Transitions to "needed" are immediate; transitions to "idle" wait
        NBP_BLE_AUTO_OFF_IDLE_SECS to avoid churn on brief HA/WiFi blips.

config NBP_BLE_AUTO_OFF_IDLE_SECS
    int "Auto-off: idle grace period before quiescing (seconds)"
    depends on NBP_BLE_AUTO_OFF
    default 30
    help
        How long a role must stay continuously idle before it is
        quiesced. Guards against toggling the radio on every HA
        reconnect or transient WiFi drop. Re-activation is always
        immediate regardless of this value.

config NBP_CLONE
    bool "BLE clone: local GATT mirror of one upstream device"
    default n
    select BT_NIMBLE_ROLE_PERIPHERAL  if BT_NIMBLE_ENABLED
    select BT_NIMBLE_ROLE_BROADCASTER if BT_NIMBLE_ENABLED
    select BT_NIMBLE_NVS_PERSIST      if BT_NIMBLE_ENABLED
    help
        Scan for a configured upstream peripheral (target MAC stored in
        NVS), connect to it as a central, walk its GATT database, then
        expose an identical local GATT server that proxies every
        read / write / subscribe back to the upstream link.

        Multiple local centrals (e.g. HA phone app + vendor app) can
        connect simultaneously and all see the same upstream device.
        NimBLE handles notification fan-out natively; writes from N
        centrals serialize through one upstream mutex.

        The ESPHome-style scanner + raw-advertisement forwarding keeps
        running. Clone uses one of the BT_NIMBLE_MAX_CONNECTIONS slots
        for its upstream link; local centrals also consume slots while
        connected. Consider bumping BT_NIMBLE_MAX_CONNECTIONS by the
        number of simultaneous local centrals you expect.

        Costs ~20 KB flash and ~10-15 KB RAM when active and a device
        is cloned. NimBLE GATT registration is one-shot, so re-targeting
        requires a reboot: POST /clone?addr=...&type=N then reboot.

config NBP_CLONE_BOOT_GUARD
    bool "Clone: disable on next boot if previous boot panicked early"
    depends on NBP_CLONE
    default y
    help
        Boot-loop safety net. At app_main start, check esp_reset_reason()
        and a "boot_pending" flag in NVS (namespace nbp_boot). If the
        previous run set the flag and this boot was triggered by a
        crash-class reset (panic, INT/TASK/WDT, brownout), force-disable
        the clone target (clone_config: enabled=false) before
        ble_clone::init() runs, so the next reboot does not repeat the
        same crash path.

        The flag is rearmed on every boot and cleared by an esp_timer
        one-shot after CONFIG_NBP_CLONE_BOOT_GUARD_SECS seconds of
        uptime. The user can re-enable clone via POST /clone after
        fixing the underlying issue.

        Turn off if you'd rather have the device keep retrying clone
        across crashes (e.g. you trust the upstream and want to ride out
        transient panics).

config NBP_CLONE_BOOT_GUARD_SECS
    int "Clone: boot-guard stable-uptime window (seconds)"
    depends on NBP_CLONE_BOOT_GUARD
    default 60
    range 10 600
    help
        How long the device must stay up without a crash-class reset
        before the boot-pending flag is cleared. A panic that happens
        after this window does not trigger the force-disable path; the
        problem is treated as runtime, not boot-time.

config NBP_CLONE_MAX_CHARS
    int "Clone: max characteristics to mirror"
    depends on NBP_CLONE
    default 64
    range 8 256
    help
        Caps the local GATT-DB attribute table. Each slot also reserves
        a value-cache buffer (NBP_CLONE_VALUE_CACHE_BYTES below). Bumps
        BSS by ~(cache_bytes + 40) per slot.

config NBP_CLONE_VALUE_CACHE_BYTES
    int "Clone: per-char cached value buffer (bytes)"
    depends on NBP_CLONE
    default 64
    range 20 244
    help
        Size of the per-characteristic read cache. The first read from a
        local central hits this cache so HA's GATT connect doesn't stall
        on N synchronous upstream reads. Writes invalidate the cache.

config NBP_SMP
    bool "Enable central-side SMP / static-passkey pairing support"
    default y
    select BT_NIMBLE_SECURITY_ENABLE if BT_NIMBLE_ENABLED
    select BT_NIMBLE_SM_LEGACY        if BT_NIMBLE_ENABLED
    select BT_NIMBLE_SM_SC            if BT_NIMBLE_ENABLED
    select BT_NIMBLE_NVS_PERSIST      if BT_NIMBLE_ENABLED
    help
        Compile in NimBLE Security Manager + bond storage. Required for
        peripherals that demand a paired+encrypted link with a static
        passkey (Victron SmartShunt, some BMS variants). On first
        connect the proxy auto-pairs using the passkey configured via
        POST /clone?passkey=NNNNNN (default 123456, NVS-persisted,
        runtime-mutable). The bond is stored in NVS so subsequent
        connects reuse it.

        Disable for a smaller central-only build (~5 KB binary + a few
        hundred bytes of NVS). With this off, peers that require
        encryption will return an authentication-required error on
        their characteristics; reads/writes/notifies on non-encrypted
        chars still work normally.

config NBP_DEVICES_PANEL
    bool "Web UI: live device table (/devices + dashboard table)"
    default y
    help
        Track every unique MAC the scanner sees in a 64-entry table
        (RSSI, last local name, cumulative adv count, last-seen
        timestamp; LRU-by-last_ms eviction). Exposes it as a JSON
        endpoint at /devices and renders a sortable table below the
        rate chart on the dashboard.

        Costs ~12 KB BSS (two 3 KB DeviceRow arrays + 6 KB JSON
        scratch buffer) plus one extra mutex op per advertisement.
        Disable for a slimmer build that keeps the rate chart but
        drops the per-device view.

config NBP_BTHOME
    bool "Web UI: decode BTHome v2 service-data adverts (/devices column)"
    depends on NBP_DEVICES_PANEL
    default y
    help
        Decode BTHome v2 (https://bthome.io) service-data
        advertisements (16-bit UUID 0xFCD2) inline in the scan
        callback and surface the most recent reading (temperature,
        humidity, battery, voltage, illuminance, motion, button,
        power, CO2, packet id) as a "BTHome" column in the existing
        /devices table on the dashboard.

        Encrypted BTHome frames are detected and marked but not
        decrypted — per-device key configuration is not yet
        implemented. Unrecognized object IDs abort the rest of that
        frame (BTHome has no separators) but preserve any fields
        already decoded before the unknown ID.

        Costs ~1.5 KB BSS (32-entry cache + scratch) plus one
        optional mutex op per advert (only when 0xFCD2 service data
        is present). The raw-advertisement forwarding path to Home
        Assistant is unchanged — this is a parallel local-display
        path.

config NBP_DEV_DETAILS
    bool "Web UI: enrich /devices with appearance, connectable, vendor tag"
    depends on NBP_DEVICES_PANEL
    default y
    help
        Decode the extra fields each advertisement carries beyond
        MAC + name + RSSI: GAP Appearance (AD 0x19, rendered as an
        emoji prefix on the name), connectable PDU flag (used to hide
        the clone button for broadcast-only sensors / beacons), and
        a vendor / class tag derived from manufacturer company ID
        (Apple Continuity subtypes, Microsoft, Samsung, Google, Sony,
        Bose, Sonos, Tile, Ruuvi, Victron, Xiaomi, Anker, Nordic,
        Espressif, Garmin, LG, Sennheiser, iBeacon, AltBeacon) or
        16-bit service UUID (BTHome, FastPair, Eddystone, ENS,
        MiBeacon, SwitchBot, Battery, EnvSense, HID, HeartRate,
        Cycling, DevInfo).

        Costs ~1 KB BSS (4 bytes × 64 rows + label tables in flash)
        plus a small AD walk per advertisement. Disable for a slim
        build that keeps just MAC / name / RSSI / counts in the
        device table; the address-type column derived client-side
        from the MAC stays either way.

endif # NBP_BLE

config NBP_WEB_CONSOLE
    bool "Web UI: device log mirror (/log + on-page console)"
    default y
    help
        Tee esp_log_set_vprintf into a ring buffer and stream it to
        the dashboard. /log?since=N returns new bytes via chunked
        encoding; the page polls every 500 ms and renders ANSI
        colors via ansi_up. UART/JTAG output is unaffected — this
        is purely a copy.

        Ring sizes itself from CONFIG_BT_NIMBLE_LOG_LEVEL_DEBUG:
        64 KiB with NimBLE DEBUG on, 8 KiB otherwise. The 64 KiB
        path is the dashboard's largest BSS consumer; disable here
        if you don't need the web console (UART logging stays).

endmenu
